WEBVTT

NOTE
This file was generated by Descript <www.descript.com>

00:00:05.349 --> 00:00:08.219
Hello, hello, hello, and welcome

00:00:08.219 --> 00:00:10.139
to English Learning for Curious

00:00:10.139 --> 00:00:12.989
Minds, by Leonardo English, the show

00:00:13.009 --> 00:00:14.629
where you can listen to fascinating

00:00:14.629 --> 00:00:17.219
stories and learn weird and wonderful

00:00:17.229 --> 00:00:19.229
things about the world at the same

00:00:19.229 --> 00:00:20.939
time as improving your English.

00:00:21.459 --> 00:00:24.599
I'm Alastair Budge, and today it’s part

00:00:24.639 --> 00:00:27.709
two of our three-part mini-series on

00:00:27.709 --> 00:00:30.169
the theme of the history of animals.

00:00:30.649 --> 00:00:32.629
In case you missed part one, we

00:00:32.629 --> 00:00:34.509
learned about man’s best friend,

00:00:34.769 --> 00:00:37.479
his loyal canine companion, the dog.

00:00:38.069 --> 00:00:41.189
Next up, in part three, we will talk about

00:00:41.199 --> 00:00:44.189
the mysterious phenomenon of dragons.

00:00:44.339 --> 00:00:47.529
But today, in part two, it’s the cat.

00:00:48.109 --> 00:00:49.839
How did they come to live with us?

00:00:50.049 --> 00:00:51.279
What do we know about them?

00:00:51.579 --> 00:00:53.019
What remains a mystery?

00:00:53.279 --> 00:00:54.949
And what are some of the most

00:00:55.009 --> 00:00:57.499
interesting and unusual facts

00:00:57.609 --> 00:00:59.279
about cats through history.

00:00:59.939 --> 00:01:02.249
We have a lot to get through, so let’s

00:01:02.249 --> 00:01:05.523
not waste a minute, and get right into it.

00:01:07.269 --> 00:01:09.949
The cat is, by some measures, the

00:01:09.959 --> 00:01:11.949
second most popular animal in the

00:01:11.949 --> 00:01:13.979
world, after the dog of course.

00:01:14.929 --> 00:01:17.829
There are an estimated 600 million

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:20.689
worldwide, of whom just over a

00:01:20.749 --> 00:01:23.879
third are domesticated, house cats.

00:01:24.730 --> 00:01:27.169
Perhaps you are listening to this episode

00:01:27.169 --> 00:01:30.229
right now with a cat purring beside you,

00:01:30.549 --> 00:01:32.729
or there is one on your lap which you

00:01:32.729 --> 00:01:35.919
are stroking in a Bond-villain-esque way.

00:01:37.309 --> 00:01:40.129
The strange thing is, for the second most

00:01:40.149 --> 00:01:42.899
popular animal in the world, we actually

00:01:42.899 --> 00:01:45.539
know remarkably little about cats.

00:01:46.709 --> 00:01:50.039
We don't fully understand why they purr.

00:01:50.599 --> 00:01:51.969
There are theories, but

00:01:52.299 --> 00:01:54.209
no scientific consensus.

00:01:55.069 --> 00:01:57.569
We don't know exactly why they

00:01:57.569 --> 00:01:59.809
bring us dead mice and birds.

00:02:00.529 --> 00:02:01.949
Are they teaching us to hunt?

00:02:02.509 --> 00:02:03.629
Offering gifts?

00:02:04.019 --> 00:02:05.289
Showing off their skills?

00:02:05.949 --> 00:02:07.969
Nobody really knows for sure.

00:02:09.059 --> 00:02:11.619
We're not entirely sure why adult

00:02:11.649 --> 00:02:14.719
cats knead with their paws, pushing

00:02:14.779 --> 00:02:16.939
in and out like they're making bread.

00:02:18.279 --> 00:02:20.679
And perhaps most mysteriously of all,

00:02:21.029 --> 00:02:23.829
we don't really know why cats decided

00:02:23.829 --> 00:02:25.709
to live with us in the first place.

00:02:27.399 --> 00:02:31.019
Unlike dogs, who co-evolved alongside

00:02:31.019 --> 00:02:33.729
humans over tens of thousands of years,

00:02:34.049 --> 00:02:37.009
developing an almost telepathic ability

00:02:37.279 --> 00:02:40.799
to read our gestures and emotions, cats

00:02:41.159 --> 00:02:45.539
remain, well, inscrutable, mysterious.

00:02:46.299 --> 00:02:48.099
They live in our homes.

00:02:48.299 --> 00:02:49.669
They sleep on our beds.

00:02:49.939 --> 00:02:52.239
They grace us with their presence.

00:02:52.909 --> 00:02:55.699
But they do so on their own

00:02:55.699 --> 00:02:57.969
terms, keeping their secrets,

00:02:58.179 --> 00:03:00.819
maintaining an air of mystery.

00:03:01.999 --> 00:03:03.999
While a dog might look at you with

00:03:04.099 --> 00:03:07.299
utter adoration, a cat will look at you

00:03:07.509 --> 00:03:10.049
with what can only be described as mild

00:03:10.059 --> 00:03:14.089
disdain, as if to say, "Yes, human, you

00:03:14.089 --> 00:03:16.299
may continue existing in my presence."

00:03:18.169 --> 00:03:21.599
And yet, despite this aloofness—or

00:03:21.749 --> 00:03:24.009
perhaps because of it—hundreds of

00:03:24.009 --> 00:03:25.639
millions of people around the world

00:03:25.949 --> 00:03:27.789
have chosen to share their homes

00:03:27.999 --> 00:03:29.959
with these enigmatic creatures.

00:03:30.659 --> 00:03:33.509
So, to understand why cats are so

00:03:33.639 --> 00:03:35.939
different from every other animal we've

00:03:35.939 --> 00:03:39.239
domesticated, and to understand why

00:03:39.459 --> 00:03:42.149
they remain so mysterious after ten

00:03:42.149 --> 00:03:44.619
thousand years of living alongside us,

00:03:44.979 --> 00:03:47.369
we need to go back to the very beginning.

00:03:47.869 --> 00:03:50.509
To a time when cats were not curled up on

00:03:50.509 --> 00:03:54.169
sofas, but were wild predators prowling

00:03:54.179 --> 00:03:57.379
the edges of the world's first farms.

00:03:58.799 --> 00:04:01.289
Imagine, if you will, the Fertile

00:04:01.329 --> 00:04:03.659
Crescent about ten thousand years ago.

00:04:04.919 --> 00:04:07.609
This region, which spanned parts

00:04:07.609 --> 00:04:10.259
of modern-day Iraq, Syria, Turkey,

00:04:10.269 --> 00:04:12.969
and Iran, this was where humans

00:04:12.979 --> 00:04:15.159
first figured out agriculture.

00:04:16.429 --> 00:04:18.979
Instead of following herds of wild

00:04:18.979 --> 00:04:21.719
animals and gathering whatever plants they

00:04:21.719 --> 00:04:25.339
could find, humans began to plant crops,

00:04:25.659 --> 00:04:29.009
harvest grain, and store it for later use.

00:04:30.261 --> 00:04:32.061
This was revolutionary.

00:04:32.591 --> 00:04:34.761
It meant staying in one place.

00:04:35.011 --> 00:04:37.451
It meant building permanent settlements.

00:04:37.831 --> 00:04:39.244
It meant the birth of

00:04:39.244 --> 00:04:41.398
civilisation as we know it.

00:04:42.581 --> 00:04:44.271
But there was a problem.

00:04:45.511 --> 00:04:48.181
Grain stores attracted mice

00:04:48.221 --> 00:04:50.571
and rats by the bucketload.

00:04:51.831 --> 00:04:54.421
But with the mice and rats came other

00:04:54.421 --> 00:04:57.021
animals, predators that hunted them.

00:04:58.322 --> 00:05:01.962
Enter the African wildcat, a small,

00:05:02.152 --> 00:05:04.402
sandy-coloured cat native to the

00:05:04.402 --> 00:05:06.292
Middle East and North Africa.

00:05:07.802 --> 00:05:10.787
These wildcats were solitary hunters,

00:05:10.832 --> 00:05:13.052
and excellent at what they did.

00:05:14.322 --> 00:05:16.692
And they quickly realised that these

00:05:16.722 --> 00:05:19.402
human grain stores were essentially

00:05:19.632 --> 00:05:22.732
an all-you-can-eat buffet of rodents.

00:05:23.622 --> 00:05:25.522
So they moved in.

00:05:26.282 --> 00:05:28.502
Not because humans encouraged

00:05:28.502 --> 00:05:29.972
them or invited them.

00:05:30.302 --> 00:05:31.132
Not because humans

00:05:31.132 --> 00:05:32.772
captured and tamed them.

00:05:33.452 --> 00:05:36.242
They moved in because it made sense.

00:05:37.582 --> 00:05:39.412
And here's where the story

00:05:39.412 --> 00:05:41.952
of cats diverges dramatically

00:05:41.962 --> 00:05:43.532
from the story of dogs.

00:05:44.232 --> 00:05:46.452
Dogs, as we learned in the

00:05:46.462 --> 00:05:48.512
previous episode, went through a

00:05:48.542 --> 00:05:51.338
process of self-domestication over

00:05:51.468 --> 00:05:53.172
thirty thousand years or more.

00:05:54.042 --> 00:05:57.112
The wolves that became dogs changed

00:05:57.152 --> 00:05:59.042
profoundly, in their physical

00:05:59.042 --> 00:06:00.332
appearance, in terms of their

00:06:00.332 --> 00:06:02.562
behaviour, and even genetically.

00:06:03.392 --> 00:06:06.132
Their snouts shortened, their ears

00:06:06.172 --> 00:06:08.502
flopped, they developed the ability

00:06:08.672 --> 00:06:11.162
to digest human food, they even

00:06:11.162 --> 00:06:13.462
grew a special muscle to make those

00:06:13.532 --> 00:06:15.582
irresistible "puppy dog eyes."

00:06:16.682 --> 00:06:18.522
Cats did none of this.

00:06:19.122 --> 00:06:21.772
Cats domesticated themselves too,

00:06:22.082 --> 00:06:24.702
in a sense, but firstly, they

00:06:24.702 --> 00:06:26.842
did it much more recently, only

00:06:26.842 --> 00:06:28.462
about ten thousand years ago.

00:06:29.072 --> 00:06:32.182
And secondly, they did it incompletely.

00:06:33.132 --> 00:06:36.212
Genetically, your pet cat is around

00:06:36.222 --> 00:06:40.022
95% identical to its wild ancestor.

00:06:40.972 --> 00:06:43.032
A modern house cat can still

00:06:43.042 --> 00:06:45.416
breed with an African wildcat

00:06:45.502 --> 00:06:47.382
and produce fertile offspring.

00:06:48.522 --> 00:06:50.862
Or to put another way: cats

00:06:51.092 --> 00:06:52.922
are barely domesticated at all.

00:06:54.392 --> 00:06:56.702
And this goes a long way to

00:06:56.702 --> 00:06:58.192
explaining their behaviour.

00:06:59.052 --> 00:07:01.522
A dog has been bred for thousands of

00:07:01.522 --> 00:07:04.582
generations to understand humans, to

00:07:04.802 --> 00:07:07.822
work with humans, to please humans.

00:07:08.752 --> 00:07:09.232
A cat?

00:07:09.862 --> 00:07:11.142
A cat just needs to be good

00:07:11.272 --> 00:07:12.742
at killing small animals.

00:07:13.142 --> 00:07:15.082
It doesn't need to understand

00:07:15.082 --> 00:07:16.572
your pointing gestures.

00:07:16.812 --> 00:07:17.852
It doesn't need to look

00:07:17.852 --> 00:07:19.312
to you for guidance.

00:07:19.832 --> 00:07:21.722
It doesn't need to care whether

00:07:21.722 --> 00:07:23.212
you're happy with it or not.

00:07:24.392 --> 00:07:26.622
Because for most of its history

00:07:26.622 --> 00:07:29.992
as a "domestic" animal, a cat had

00:07:29.992 --> 00:07:33.672
exactly one job: murder rodents.

00:07:34.022 --> 00:07:35.682
Kill mice and rats.

00:07:36.602 --> 00:07:38.212
If it performed that job well,

00:07:39.022 --> 00:07:40.902
humans tolerated its presence.

00:07:41.202 --> 00:07:43.232
There was no partnership, no

00:07:43.542 --> 00:07:45.972
co-evolution of complex tasks like

00:07:46.222 --> 00:07:47.952
herding sheep or pulling sleds.

00:07:48.662 --> 00:07:51.792
Cats simply existed near humans

00:07:52.202 --> 00:07:54.322
because it was mutually beneficial.

00:07:55.022 --> 00:07:56.942
Humans got pest control.

00:07:57.392 --> 00:07:59.312
Cats got easy meals.

00:08:00.642 --> 00:08:02.642
And critically, in the early

00:08:02.642 --> 00:08:04.852
days at least, humans didn't try

00:08:04.882 --> 00:08:07.412
to breed cats for temperament.

00:08:08.362 --> 00:08:11.582
The friendly cats stuck around, sure, but

00:08:11.582 --> 00:08:13.852
there was no strong selection pressure for

00:08:13.852 --> 00:08:16.502
friendliness the way there was with dogs.

00:08:17.312 --> 00:08:20.042
A grumpy, antisocial cat that

00:08:20.042 --> 00:08:22.042
was excellent at hunting was just

00:08:22.042 --> 00:08:23.432
as valuable as a friendly one.

00:08:23.872 --> 00:08:25.402
Perhaps even more so.

00:08:26.282 --> 00:08:29.132
And this arrangement carried on for

00:08:29.132 --> 00:08:31.442
thousands of years, with cats living

00:08:31.442 --> 00:08:33.282
on the edges of human civilisation,

00:08:33.812 --> 00:08:35.862
tolerated but not treasured.

00:08:37.012 --> 00:08:40.782
Until, that is, they arrived in Egypt.

00:08:41.746 --> 00:08:44.256
If you had to pick one place and time in

00:08:44.256 --> 00:08:46.976
history when cats reached the absolute

00:08:47.096 --> 00:08:49.786
peak of their social status, it would be

00:08:49.806 --> 00:08:53.546
Ancient Egypt, starting around 3,000 BC.

00:08:54.826 --> 00:08:57.866
The Egyptians didn't just like cats.

00:08:58.026 --> 00:08:59.316
They worshipped them.

00:09:00.416 --> 00:09:02.416
One of the most important gods

00:09:02.536 --> 00:09:04.526
in ancient Egypt was called

00:09:04.556 --> 00:09:06.646
Bastet, or Bast for short.

00:09:07.736 --> 00:09:10.846
She was the goddess of home, fertility,

00:09:11.116 --> 00:09:13.776
childbirth, and protection, and she

00:09:13.776 --> 00:09:16.336
was depicted either as a woman with

00:09:16.336 --> 00:09:19.756
the head of a cat, or simply as a cat.

00:09:21.136 --> 00:09:23.986
Cats themselves became sacred animals.

00:09:24.736 --> 00:09:27.326
Killing a cat, even accidentally,

00:09:27.646 --> 00:09:29.316
was punishable by death.

00:09:30.676 --> 00:09:33.406
When a family's cat died, the members

00:09:33.436 --> 00:09:35.586
of the household would go into mourning,

00:09:35.956 --> 00:09:38.846
shaving their eyebrows as a sign of grief.

00:09:39.866 --> 00:09:42.186
Cats were mummified and buried with

00:09:42.216 --> 00:09:45.436
great ceremony, sometimes with mummified

00:09:45.446 --> 00:09:48.026
mice to sustain them in the afterlife.

00:09:49.036 --> 00:09:52.496
In 1888, an Egyptian farmer discovered

00:09:52.496 --> 00:09:55.746
a cat cemetery containing an estimated

00:09:56.106 --> 00:09:58.796
eighty thousand mummified cats.

00:09:59.196 --> 00:10:00.206
Eighty thousand.

00:10:01.316 --> 00:10:03.926
Now, why do people believe the Egyptians

00:10:03.926 --> 00:10:05.966
were so intensely fond of cats?

00:10:06.786 --> 00:10:10.296
Well, partly, it was probably practical.

00:10:11.266 --> 00:10:13.546
Egypt's economy was particularly

00:10:13.566 --> 00:10:16.406
dependent on grain, and cats

00:10:16.476 --> 00:10:18.186
protected that grain from rodents.

00:10:18.846 --> 00:10:21.216
But it was deeper than that.

00:10:22.226 --> 00:10:24.326
Cats were seen as embodying

00:10:24.346 --> 00:10:26.596
qualities the Egyptians admired:

00:10:27.116 --> 00:10:29.926
grace, cleanliness, being fierce

00:10:29.956 --> 00:10:32.516
when necessary, and calm when not.

00:10:33.406 --> 00:10:35.646
A cat could be a loving presence in the

00:10:35.646 --> 00:10:38.556
home, and a ruthless killer of pests.

00:10:39.036 --> 00:10:41.686
It was the perfect animal, the embodiment

00:10:41.886 --> 00:10:44.216
of everything ancient Egypt stood for.

00:10:45.122 --> 00:10:47.792
And there's a famous story, or

00:10:47.842 --> 00:10:50.142
legend, perhaps, that illustrates

00:10:50.162 --> 00:10:52.292
just how seriously the Egyptians

00:10:52.292 --> 00:10:53.842
took their cat worship.

00:10:55.072 --> 00:10:59.142
In 525 BCE, the Persian army laid

00:10:59.152 --> 00:11:02.182
siege to the Egyptian city of Pelusium.

00:11:03.316 --> 00:11:05.786
According to one report, the Persians

00:11:05.836 --> 00:11:08.956
knew about the Egyptians' mania for cats.

00:11:09.906 --> 00:11:12.266
The Persian soldiers, so the story

00:11:12.266 --> 00:11:15.706
goes, painted images of the cat goddess

00:11:15.786 --> 00:11:18.786
Bastet on their shields, and either

00:11:18.816 --> 00:11:21.856
carried live cats into battle or released

00:11:21.876 --> 00:11:24.246
hundreds of cats onto the battlefield.

00:11:25.586 --> 00:11:28.066
The Egyptian soldiers were completely

00:11:28.156 --> 00:11:30.726
unwilling to risk harming a single

00:11:30.726 --> 00:11:33.726
cat, so they refused to fight back.

00:11:34.506 --> 00:11:37.586
And the city fell without much resistance.

00:11:39.036 --> 00:11:41.316
Now, there are some question marks

00:11:41.466 --> 00:11:43.416
as to whether this actually happened,

00:11:43.726 --> 00:11:45.746
but the fact that the story exists

00:11:45.766 --> 00:11:48.546
at all gives us an indication of how

00:11:48.546 --> 00:11:50.896
highly cats were prized in Egypt.

00:11:51.356 --> 00:11:53.186
They weren't just pets.

00:11:53.406 --> 00:11:54.156
They were sacred.

00:11:55.546 --> 00:11:57.716
And because Egypt was a major

00:11:57.716 --> 00:12:00.366
trading power, cats didn't stay

00:12:00.366 --> 00:12:02.186
confined to the Nile Valley.

00:12:03.166 --> 00:12:05.836
The Egyptians tried to ban the export

00:12:05.836 --> 00:12:08.566
of cats, considering them too valuable,

00:12:08.876 --> 00:12:11.964
but Phoenician traders smuggled them out

00:12:12.076 --> 00:12:14.286
and sold them across the Mediterranean.

00:12:15.386 --> 00:12:18.406
Cats spread via trade routes and ships,

00:12:18.656 --> 00:12:20.796
where they served a vital function:

00:12:21.436 --> 00:12:24.210
pest control on long sea voyages.

00:12:25.686 --> 00:12:27.906
By Roman times, cats were found

00:12:27.916 --> 00:12:30.616
throughout Europe, Asia, and North Africa.

00:12:31.346 --> 00:12:33.586
But their fortunes were

00:12:33.616 --> 00:12:35.876
about to take a dark turn.

00:12:37.146 --> 00:12:39.456
If Ancient Egypt represented the

00:12:39.556 --> 00:12:41.866
peak of the cat's status in human

00:12:41.866 --> 00:12:44.886
society, medieval Europe represented

00:12:44.976 --> 00:12:48.006
its absolute nadir, its lowest point.

00:12:49.330 --> 00:12:51.940
As Christianity spread across Europe

00:12:52.060 --> 00:12:54.520
in the early medieval period, cats

00:12:54.780 --> 00:12:56.900
began to be viewed with suspicion.

00:12:58.240 --> 00:12:58.690
Why?

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:01.040
Well, partly because of their

00:13:01.040 --> 00:13:03.500
association with pagan religions.

00:13:04.380 --> 00:13:05.903
After all, they'd been

00:13:05.903 --> 00:13:07.470
worshipped as gods in Egypt.

00:13:07.980 --> 00:13:09.810
But there was something else.

00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:12.950
Cats were independent.

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:14.050
Aloof.

00:13:14.510 --> 00:13:15.780
Impossible to control.

00:13:16.940 --> 00:13:19.360
Dogs were obedient, loyal, seen

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:21.950
as "natural" companions to humans.

00:13:22.690 --> 00:13:25.330
Cats, on the other hand, came

00:13:25.330 --> 00:13:26.770
and went as they pleased.

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:28.350
They hunted at night.

00:13:28.700 --> 00:13:30.920
They seemed to answer to no one.

00:13:32.290 --> 00:13:33.890
In a religious and social

00:13:33.890 --> 00:13:36.480
order that valued obedience and

00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:39.160
hierarchy, the cat's independence

00:13:39.450 --> 00:13:42.320
was seen as almost... unnatural.

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:47.520
And by the 13th century, this suspicion

00:13:47.850 --> 00:13:51.050
had transformed into something far darker.

00:13:52.170 --> 00:13:55.560
Cats, particularly black cats, became

00:13:55.560 --> 00:13:58.970
associated with witchcraft and the devil.

00:14:00.340 --> 00:14:03.420
The logic, such as it was, went

00:14:03.430 --> 00:14:06.480
something like this: witches were in

00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:09.220
league with Satan, and Satan could

00:14:09.230 --> 00:14:11.620
send them animal companions called

00:14:11.670 --> 00:14:13.700
'familiars' to do their bidding.

00:14:14.930 --> 00:14:17.213
What better familiar than a cat?

00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:20.470
An animal that prowled at night, that

00:14:20.470 --> 00:14:23.373
seemed to see in the darkness, that

00:14:23.383 --> 00:14:26.293
moved silently and killed without mercy?

00:14:27.583 --> 00:14:31.253
Pope Gregory IX allegedly issued a papal

00:14:31.253 --> 00:14:35.453
decree in 1233 called Vox in Rama, which

00:14:35.473 --> 00:14:38.213
condemned cats as instruments of Satan.

00:14:38.993 --> 00:14:42.063
Now, historians debate whether this decree

00:14:42.073 --> 00:14:45.243
specifically targeted cats, or whether

00:14:45.243 --> 00:14:47.946
it was more broadly about heresy, but

00:14:48.213 --> 00:14:50.583
regardless, the result was the same.

00:14:51.723 --> 00:14:53.723
Across Europe, particularly

00:14:54.033 --> 00:14:55.443
during the height of the witch

00:14:55.443 --> 00:14:58.223
trials from the 13th to the 17th

00:14:58.233 --> 00:15:01.183
centuries, cats were persecuted.

00:15:01.553 --> 00:15:03.363
They were killed en masse.

00:15:03.613 --> 00:15:04.653
Burned alive.

00:15:04.953 --> 00:15:06.403
Thrown from towers.

00:15:06.843 --> 00:15:08.063
Hunted for sport.

00:15:09.183 --> 00:15:11.573
In some towns, killing cats

00:15:11.783 --> 00:15:13.533
became a form of entertainment.

00:15:14.263 --> 00:15:15.673
In France, there was a

00:15:15.703 --> 00:15:18.033
tradition of burning bags of

00:15:18.053 --> 00:15:20.493
live cats as part of festivals.

00:15:21.263 --> 00:15:23.993
If you were a cat, well, life in Medieval

00:15:24.003 --> 00:15:26.353
France was about as bad as it got.

00:15:27.753 --> 00:15:31.913
And then, in 1347, came the consequences.

00:15:32.723 --> 00:15:34.903
The Black Death arrived in Europe,

00:15:35.213 --> 00:15:37.373
likely via trading ships from Asia.

00:15:37.995 --> 00:15:40.575
The plague was caused by a bacterium

00:15:41.042 --> 00:15:44.302
carried by fleas that lived on black rats.

00:15:45.222 --> 00:15:47.472
Now, you probably know something about The

00:15:47.472 --> 00:15:49.602
Black Death already, and we also have an

00:15:49.612 --> 00:15:52.895
episode on it; it’s episode number 129.

00:15:53.652 --> 00:15:56.542
Long story short, it would kill somewhere

00:15:56.542 --> 00:16:00.772
between 75 and 200 million people—roughly

00:16:00.892 --> 00:16:03.762
one-third of Europe's entire population.

00:16:04.972 --> 00:16:08.742
And here's the bitter irony: Europeans

00:16:08.942 --> 00:16:10.592
had spent the previous century

00:16:10.882 --> 00:16:13.072
killing the one animal that could have

00:16:13.072 --> 00:16:15.162
helped control the rat population.

00:16:16.052 --> 00:16:16.562
Cats.

00:16:17.659 --> 00:16:20.319
Now, to be clear, no historian is

00:16:20.319 --> 00:16:22.659
suggesting that cats alone could have

00:16:22.659 --> 00:16:25.559
stopped the plague, but more cats

00:16:25.789 --> 00:16:27.749
would have meant fewer rats, which

00:16:27.749 --> 00:16:29.519
would have meant fewer plague-carrying

00:16:29.519 --> 00:16:31.769
fleas, and fewer dead bodies.

00:16:32.899 --> 00:16:34.929
It was one of history's great tragic

00:16:34.979 --> 00:16:37.539
ironies, a cautionary tale about the

00:16:37.559 --> 00:16:40.619
dangers of superstition and mass hysteria.

00:16:41.809 --> 00:16:44.559
And while Europe was busy persecuting

00:16:44.579 --> 00:16:46.709
cats, other parts of the world

00:16:46.939 --> 00:16:48.419
took a very different view.

00:16:49.785 --> 00:16:51.885
In the Islamic world, cats

00:16:52.045 --> 00:16:53.965
remained popular and respected.

00:16:54.565 --> 00:16:55.985
The Prophet Muhammad was

00:16:55.985 --> 00:16:57.345
said to have loved cats.

00:16:57.985 --> 00:17:01.115
In Islamic culture, cats were considered

00:17:01.235 --> 00:17:04.375
clean animals, unlike dogs, and were

00:17:04.375 --> 00:17:07.085
welcome in homes and even mosques.

00:17:07.785 --> 00:17:09.715
They remained valued for their pest

00:17:09.745 --> 00:17:12.115
control abilities and their companionship.

00:17:13.235 --> 00:17:15.385
Similarly, in parts of Asia,

00:17:15.775 --> 00:17:17.585
cats maintained their status.

00:17:18.535 --> 00:17:20.955
In Japan, where cats had arrived

00:17:21.005 --> 00:17:23.115
around the 6th century, they

00:17:23.115 --> 00:17:24.755
became culturally significant.

00:17:25.415 --> 00:17:27.685
They appeared in art and literature,

00:17:28.075 --> 00:17:30.045
and eventually became symbols

00:17:30.045 --> 00:17:32.505
of good fortune—think of the

00:17:32.735 --> 00:17:34.945
Maneki-neko, the "lucky cat"

00:17:34.975 --> 00:17:37.245
figurine you see in Japanese shops.

00:17:38.711 --> 00:17:40.721
Back in Europe, however, it would

00:17:40.731 --> 00:17:42.991
take several more centuries before

00:17:42.991 --> 00:17:45.221
cats could shake off their demonic

00:17:45.221 --> 00:17:47.570
reputation and return to human favour.

00:17:49.081 --> 00:17:52.041
The rehabilitation of the cat in European

00:17:52.041 --> 00:17:55.991
society began slowly, but by the 19th

00:17:56.031 --> 00:17:59.171
century, cats were firmly back in fashion.

00:18:00.631 --> 00:18:03.551
During the Victorian era, the same

00:18:03.561 --> 00:18:05.921
period when dogs were transitioning

00:18:05.921 --> 00:18:08.481
from workers to companions, cats

00:18:08.651 --> 00:18:10.321
saw a similar transformation.

00:18:11.251 --> 00:18:13.471
But there was a key difference.

00:18:14.541 --> 00:18:17.581
Victorian society loved to classify,

00:18:17.831 --> 00:18:20.181
categorise, and "improve" things

00:18:20.451 --> 00:18:21.791
through selective breeding.

00:18:22.991 --> 00:18:26.231
And cats, unlike dogs, had never

00:18:26.231 --> 00:18:28.241
really been bred for specific

00:18:28.291 --> 00:18:31.641
purposes beyond basic mousing ability.

00:18:32.877 --> 00:18:34.877
This was about to change.

00:18:35.887 --> 00:18:40.197
In July 1871, the first major cat show

00:18:40.537 --> 00:18:43.017
was held at the Crystal Palace in London.

00:18:44.157 --> 00:18:46.997
It was organised by a man named Harrison

00:18:46.997 --> 00:18:49.857
Weir, an artist and cat enthusiast

00:18:50.177 --> 00:18:51.737
who wanted to elevate the status

00:18:51.737 --> 00:18:53.877
of cats and promote their breeding.

00:18:55.117 --> 00:18:58.287
The show featured over 160 cats,

00:18:58.457 --> 00:19:00.547
and it was a massive success.

00:19:01.277 --> 00:19:03.797
Thousands of people came to see cats

00:19:03.797 --> 00:19:05.937
of different colours, patterns, and

00:19:05.937 --> 00:19:08.357
coat lengths, all competing for prizes.

00:19:09.657 --> 00:19:11.957
This event sparked the beginning of

00:19:11.957 --> 00:19:15.297
the "cat fancy"—the deliberate breeding

00:19:15.297 --> 00:19:18.337
of cats for specific aesthetic traits.

00:19:19.587 --> 00:19:22.957
Suddenly, cats weren't just mousers

00:19:22.957 --> 00:19:25.347
or companions; they were status

00:19:25.357 --> 00:19:27.437
symbols, living works of art.

00:19:28.761 --> 00:19:32.071
But perhaps the real reason cats made such

00:19:32.071 --> 00:19:34.611
a successful comeback in the Victorian

00:19:34.641 --> 00:19:37.181
era and beyond had less to do with

00:19:37.191 --> 00:19:39.991
fashion and more to do with practicality.

00:19:41.111 --> 00:19:43.891
As Europe and North America urbanised

00:19:43.901 --> 00:19:46.581
rapidly in the 19th and 20th centuries,

00:19:46.941 --> 00:19:49.531
more and more people moved into cities,

00:19:49.531 --> 00:19:51.971
into smaller homes and apartments.

00:19:52.651 --> 00:19:54.671
Dogs required space.

00:19:54.941 --> 00:19:56.551
They needed daily walks.

00:19:56.571 --> 00:19:58.681
They demanded attention and training.

00:19:58.881 --> 00:20:00.581
They needed to go outside

00:20:00.791 --> 00:20:01.631
to go to the toilet.

00:20:02.751 --> 00:20:05.121
Cats, on the other hand, were

00:20:05.161 --> 00:20:06.881
perfect for urban living.

00:20:07.361 --> 00:20:09.191
They were self-sufficient.

00:20:09.481 --> 00:20:10.951
They didn't need to be walked.

00:20:11.111 --> 00:20:13.551
They were happy in smaller spaces.

00:20:14.501 --> 00:20:16.881
They were, in short, the ideal

00:20:16.881 --> 00:20:18.961
pet for the modern city dweller.

00:20:20.234 --> 00:20:23.894
And then, in 1947, came an invention

00:20:24.074 --> 00:20:25.834
that would change cat ownership

00:20:25.904 --> 00:20:28.554
forever: the cat litter box.

00:20:29.797 --> 00:20:32.997
Before this, cats either went outside

00:20:33.007 --> 00:20:35.127
to do their business, or they used

00:20:35.127 --> 00:20:37.637
boxes filled with sand or ashes,

00:20:37.927 --> 00:20:40.257
which were messy and smelled terrible.

00:20:41.467 --> 00:20:43.257
An American businessman called

00:20:43.317 --> 00:20:45.597
Edward Lowe had a breakthrough.

00:20:47.057 --> 00:20:49.317
He discovered that a particular

00:20:49.317 --> 00:20:52.367
type of absorbent clay worked

00:20:52.417 --> 00:20:54.377
brilliantly for this purpose.

00:20:55.451 --> 00:20:58.071
He packaged it, called it "Kitty Litter,"

00:20:58.421 --> 00:21:01.351
and created an entirely new industry.

00:21:02.721 --> 00:21:05.901
Suddenly, keeping a cat indoors full-time

00:21:06.291 --> 00:21:09.171
became not just possible, but pleasant.

00:21:10.361 --> 00:21:12.651
And by the mid-20th century,

00:21:12.941 --> 00:21:14.481
particularly after World War

00:21:14.501 --> 00:21:17.371
II, cat ownership exploded.

00:21:18.421 --> 00:21:20.741
In many countries, cats began

00:21:20.741 --> 00:21:22.851
to rival, and in some cases

00:21:22.921 --> 00:21:25.461
overtake, dogs in popularity.

00:21:26.861 --> 00:21:29.401
Still, despite the hundreds of millions

00:21:29.401 --> 00:21:30.981
that live alongside humans today,

00:21:31.341 --> 00:21:33.491
and having lived alongside humans for

00:21:33.551 --> 00:21:36.591
ten thousand years, there's still so

00:21:36.591 --> 00:21:38.251
much we don't understand about them.

00:21:39.241 --> 00:21:41.151
Take purring, for example.

00:21:42.081 --> 00:21:44.401
You probably think you know why

00:21:44.421 --> 00:21:46.841
cats purr—they're happy, right?

00:21:47.481 --> 00:21:48.831
Well, maybe.

00:21:49.431 --> 00:21:52.011
But cats also purr when they're

00:21:52.021 --> 00:21:54.891
stressed, injured, or giving birth.

00:21:56.231 --> 00:21:58.941
Scientists have several theories.

00:21:59.651 --> 00:22:03.161
One is that purring is a self-soothing

00:22:03.161 --> 00:22:05.741
behaviour, a way for cats to calm

00:22:05.741 --> 00:22:08.041
themselves in stressful situations.

00:22:08.881 --> 00:22:10.861
Another theory suggests that the

00:22:10.871 --> 00:22:13.401
frequency of a cat's purr may

00:22:13.401 --> 00:22:15.801
actually promote healing, encouraging

00:22:15.811 --> 00:22:17.811
bone growth and reducing pain.

00:22:18.741 --> 00:22:20.841
Cats may literally be

00:22:20.911 --> 00:22:22.241
purring themselves better.

00:22:23.211 --> 00:22:25.041
But we don't know for certain.

00:22:25.521 --> 00:22:27.041
After thousands of years,

00:22:27.271 --> 00:22:29.451
the purr remains a mystery.

00:22:30.591 --> 00:22:32.821
Then there's kneading, pushing their

00:22:32.831 --> 00:22:34.831
paws in and out like they are making

00:22:34.831 --> 00:22:37.131
bread, or bringing you dead animals.

00:22:37.691 --> 00:22:39.751
There are plenty of theories about

00:22:39.791 --> 00:22:42.981
why cats do this, but no consensus.

00:22:44.504 --> 00:22:46.144
There’s a lot we don’t understand,

00:22:46.231 --> 00:22:48.194
but an increasing amount we do.

00:22:49.034 --> 00:22:50.884
Scientists have made some recent

00:22:50.884 --> 00:22:52.654
discoveries about cat behaviour

00:22:52.994 --> 00:22:54.704
that are genuinely fascinating.

00:22:55.984 --> 00:22:58.084
For one thing, we now know that

00:22:58.084 --> 00:23:00.044
cats have somewhere in the region

00:23:00.224 --> 00:23:04.114
of 276 different facial expressions.

00:23:05.384 --> 00:23:08.714
For comparison, dogs have about 27.

00:23:09.794 --> 00:23:12.504
Cats are far more expressive than

00:23:12.504 --> 00:23:14.464
we give them credit for, we just

00:23:14.614 --> 00:23:16.374
haven't learned to read them properly.

00:23:17.827 --> 00:23:19.827
Scientists have also confirmed

00:23:19.857 --> 00:23:21.557
what cat owners have long

00:23:21.557 --> 00:23:24.847
suspected: cats absolutely can

00:23:25.057 --> 00:23:26.727
recognise their owner's voice.

00:23:27.327 --> 00:23:30.297
They just... often choose not to respond.

00:23:31.487 --> 00:23:34.387
One study played recordings of strangers

00:23:34.557 --> 00:23:37.317
calling a cat's name, then recordings

00:23:37.327 --> 00:23:39.577
of the cat's owner calling its name.

00:23:40.927 --> 00:23:43.967
The cats showed clear recognition of

00:23:43.967 --> 00:23:46.467
their owner's voice—their ears moved,

00:23:46.487 --> 00:23:49.937
their pupils dilated—but they rarely

00:23:49.937 --> 00:23:52.607
bothered to actually come when called.

00:23:53.837 --> 00:23:56.747
Dogs, of course, mostly come running

00:23:56.907 --> 00:23:58.527
when they hear their owner’s voice.

00:23:59.077 --> 00:23:59.517
Cats?

00:24:00.207 --> 00:24:01.987
They think about it, decide

00:24:01.997 --> 00:24:03.247
whether it's worth their time,

00:24:03.347 --> 00:24:05.437
and then usually go back to sleep.

00:24:06.887 --> 00:24:08.947
And perhaps that's the most

00:24:08.977 --> 00:24:10.617
honest thing about cats.

00:24:11.407 --> 00:24:13.427
They live with us, but they

00:24:13.427 --> 00:24:15.157
haven't fundamentally changed

00:24:15.387 --> 00:24:16.987
who they are to please us.

00:24:17.967 --> 00:24:21.354
Your house cat is still 95% wildcat.

00:24:21.947 --> 00:24:24.257
It's still a predator, an apex

00:24:24.257 --> 00:24:26.822
hunter in a small, fluffy package.

00:24:27.432 --> 00:24:29.112
When it's kneading on your lap

00:24:29.112 --> 00:24:30.842
and purring, it's not doing

00:24:30.842 --> 00:24:32.512
it because you trained it to.

00:24:33.102 --> 00:24:35.362
It's doing it because, for

00:24:35.362 --> 00:24:36.762
whatever mysterious reason of

00:24:36.762 --> 00:24:39.422
its own, it wants or needs to.

00:24:40.872 --> 00:24:42.832
And there's one more theory about

00:24:42.832 --> 00:24:45.422
cats that I should mention, even

00:24:45.422 --> 00:24:47.422
though the scientific evidence for

00:24:47.422 --> 00:24:49.572
it is... let's say, controversial.

00:24:50.692 --> 00:24:52.332
It involves a parasite

00:24:52.562 --> 00:24:54.492
called Toxoplasma gondii.

00:24:55.772 --> 00:24:58.542
This parasite can only reproduce

00:24:58.552 --> 00:25:01.412
sexually inside a cat's digestive

00:25:01.412 --> 00:25:04.142
system, but it can infect other

00:25:04.142 --> 00:25:07.002
animals, including humans, usually

00:25:07.012 --> 00:25:09.232
through contact with cat faeces.

00:25:10.494 --> 00:25:13.114
In most people, it's harmless.

00:25:13.754 --> 00:25:15.824
But here's where it gets interesting.

00:25:16.734 --> 00:25:19.514
Some scientists have suggested that

00:25:19.564 --> 00:25:22.564
Toxoplasma might actually alter human

00:25:22.564 --> 00:25:25.964
behaviour in subtle ways, making infected

00:25:25.964 --> 00:25:29.204
people more fond of cats, more likely to

00:25:29.204 --> 00:25:32.354
keep cats, more tolerant of cat behaviour.

00:25:33.452 --> 00:25:35.942
In other words, the parasite might be

00:25:35.962 --> 00:25:38.952
manipulating us to ensure its own survival

00:25:39.222 --> 00:25:42.226
by making us like its primary host.

00:25:43.836 --> 00:25:46.586
The evidence for this is somewhat weak,

00:25:46.856 --> 00:25:49.076
and most scientists are sceptical.

00:25:49.496 --> 00:25:51.886
But if it were true, it would

00:25:51.896 --> 00:25:53.656
be the ultimate cat trick.

00:25:54.336 --> 00:25:57.276
Making us think we chose them, when

00:25:57.276 --> 00:25:59.676
really, they chose us all along.

00:26:00.746 --> 00:26:03.416
So where does this leave us with cats?

00:26:03.816 --> 00:26:06.156
They've achieved this remarkable success

00:26:06.546 --> 00:26:09.486
by being, fundamentally, themselves.

00:26:10.116 --> 00:26:11.506
They didn't co-evolve

00:26:11.526 --> 00:26:13.326
with us like dogs did.

00:26:13.726 --> 00:26:14.826
They didn't develop special

00:26:14.836 --> 00:26:17.006
muscles to make appealing faces.

00:26:17.486 --> 00:26:19.046
They didn't learn to understand

00:26:19.046 --> 00:26:20.866
our pointing gestures or

00:26:20.866 --> 00:26:22.326
look to us for guidance.

00:26:23.176 --> 00:26:25.526
They simply decided that living near

00:26:25.526 --> 00:26:28.506
humans was convenient, we decided

00:26:28.506 --> 00:26:30.026
that having them around was useful,

00:26:30.566 --> 00:26:32.636
and things progressed from there.

00:26:33.896 --> 00:26:36.186
Now, I should probably have confessed

00:26:36.506 --> 00:26:38.766
earlier on in this episode that I

00:26:38.766 --> 00:26:41.186
am more of a dog than a cat person.

00:26:42.046 --> 00:26:44.796
For me, you can’t beat the unconditional,

00:26:45.026 --> 00:26:47.196
undying loyalty and love of a dog.

00:26:48.216 --> 00:26:51.196
If you are more of a cat person, you will

00:26:51.216 --> 00:26:54.186
probably think this is simple and base.

00:26:54.636 --> 00:26:57.456
Dogs love anyone; cats

00:26:57.836 --> 00:26:59.016
make you work for it.

00:27:00.156 --> 00:27:02.696
And when a cat does decide to

00:27:02.696 --> 00:27:04.956
curl up on your lap, or head-butt

00:27:04.956 --> 00:27:06.836
your hand demanding attention,

00:27:07.186 --> 00:27:09.226
well, you know you've earned it.

00:27:09.859 --> 00:27:11.476
Or perhaps the cat is

00:27:11.476 --> 00:27:12.996
just cold and you're warm.

00:27:13.566 --> 00:27:16.166
Or perhaps it's hungry and you're useful.

00:27:17.156 --> 00:27:19.276
With cats, you never quite know.

00:27:20.326 --> 00:27:23.486
Dogs, as they say, have owners.

00:27:24.086 --> 00:27:25.626
Cats have staff.

00:27:26.906 --> 00:27:29.266
And after ten thousand years of this

00:27:29.266 --> 00:27:31.736
arrangement, I think we can quite safely

00:27:31.736 --> 00:27:34.746
say: that's exactly how they like it.

00:27:36.436 --> 00:27:38.586
OK then, that is it for today's

00:27:38.616 --> 00:27:41.476
episode on cats, the enigmatic,

00:27:41.476 --> 00:27:43.826
independent, and utterly mysterious

00:27:43.846 --> 00:27:46.256
animals that somehow convinced

00:27:46.306 --> 00:27:48.146
us to let them live in our homes.

00:27:48.756 --> 00:27:50.726
As a reminder, this was part two

00:27:50.736 --> 00:27:52.326
of our three-part mini-series

00:27:52.516 --> 00:27:54.016
on animals throughout history.

00:27:54.356 --> 00:27:56.816
Next up, in part three, we'll be talking

00:27:56.826 --> 00:27:58.446
about an animal that never existed at

00:27:58.446 --> 00:28:01.596
all, but has captured human imagination

00:28:01.866 --> 00:28:04.316
for thousands of years across almost

00:28:04.366 --> 00:28:06.796
every culture on Earth: the dragon.

00:28:07.186 --> 00:28:09.166
Fire-breathing, treasure-hoarding,

00:28:09.356 --> 00:28:11.266
princess-kidnapping dragons.

00:28:11.936 --> 00:28:13.766
You’ve been listening to English Learning

00:28:13.766 --> 00:28:16.426
for Curious Minds by Leonardo English.

00:28:16.816 --> 00:28:19.486
I'm Alastair Budge, you stay safe, and

00:28:19.486 --> 00:28:21.806
I'll catch you in the next episode.

